@flexiarg ukrns/open-the-triangle
@title Open the Triangle by Depositing Evidence
@keywords evidence, apex, tetrahedron, Krowne, openness, governance, Pareto, deposit, ontogenetic, propagation, legibility, closed-triangle, bootstrap
@audience UKRN-S design, programme coordinators, network-services leads
@tone analytic-foundational
@style pattern
@references [ukrns/ARGUMENT equity/visible-impact equity/shared-maintenance ukrns/measure-where-least-sure ukrns/design-as-function-of-evidence]

! conclusion: A distributed training programme that produces local success without depositing evidence of that success into a shared network layer remains a set of closed local sustainability triangles.  Every service event sits on an explicit axis between openness gain and governance cost; the service states which composition it is running and why.
  + context: Krowne (2003) identifies three facets of local sustainability — participatory, organisational, fiscal.  The ORP data show all three present but closed at the local level: the conditions that made a trainer's work succeed were not legible to other institutions.  Raising a fourth vertex — shareable evidence — converts isolated triangles into connected tetrahedra.  The equity-domain visible-impact pattern diagnoses the institutional-level failure to see one's own effects; this design pattern names the service-level response and the axis it recurs on.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: openness (propagation, cross-institution reuse, trust built through visibility) ↔ governance cost (ethics, data-handling infrastructure, reputational exposure).
    Real: each step's openness gain has a specific governance precondition; publishing a scaffold is cheap, a T1 wave under existing ethics is low-cost, cross-institution peer evaluation requires consent extension and data-sharing agreements.  Neither axis endpoint is free.
    Irreducible: the two cannot both be zero if network propagation is to occur.  An event that gains openness without any governance infrastructure is an ethics failure; an event that pays governance cost without a corresponding openness gain is ceremonial overhead.
    Active: the governance cost of a given step changes over time.  An institution that has run cross-institution evaluation before can carry Step 3 more cheaply than one running it for the first time; reputational exposure shifts as the network's trust infrastructure develops.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Low-governance loop: run Steps 0–2 and 4 — a complete learning loop at low governance cost, forgoing the cross-institution scaling benefit of Step 3 until the governance investment is available.  Gives up network scaling.
    (2) Governance-first: commit to Step 3 upfront and treat the governance work as foundational infrastructure for everything that follows.  Gives up time.
    (3) Subset pilot: attempt Step 3 with a small subset of institutions willing to carry the governance overhead, and report publicly on what that arrangement costs.  Gives up uniformity.
    These compositions are not ranked; each gives up different things.  The model and the evidence stay the same across all three.
  + BECAUSE:
    Krowne (2003): The local triangle sustains what exists; the apex opens it.  A local triangle invisible to the network is fully sustainable in the participatory, organisational, and fiscal senses but produces no network-level learning.  The apex is not additional work tacked onto sustainability — it is the fourth facet that makes the first three network-scalable.

    Ostrom commons governance: Which goods the commons will make collectively legible, at what cost to whom, is a decision the participating institutions must be able to see and shape.  A service that makes deposits without making costs visible forecloses governance; a service that costs every event invites negotiation.

    Ontogenetic accretion: What a completed event deposits (scaffold, T1 finding, workshop artefact, updated population model) persists as infrastructure the next event inherits.  Like growth rings — the sequence can slow, resume, or run partially, and the architecture remains legible because the deposits do not evaporate.

    Self-application: The working paper itself is a deposit.  A notebook that loads evidence, computes a model, and emits an argument is a legible artefact in a way a static PDF is not.  The paper's form instantiates the pattern it names.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: each event is explicitly costed on both openness and governance axes; the programme can say which composition it is running and why; deposits persist beyond the funding cycle of the event that produced them.
    Failing when: local success remains illegible to other institutions (the closed-triangle failure mode); each event is paid for from scratch rather than inheriting prior deposits; governance work is done for its own sake without a corresponding openness gain.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - For each planned service event, state openness gain and governance cost in the same accounting before committing to run it
    - Publish the current composition and the Pareto table supporting it so participating institutions can contest or endorse the chosen stopping point
    - Design every deposit to persist beyond the funding cycle of the event that produced it (avoid deposits that depend on a specific post, consortium, or grant for their continued legibility)
    - Treat the working paper itself as a deposit: version it, update it when the evidence base updates, and let the form be inspected
    - Use this pattern alongside ukrns/measure-where-least-sure (which selects which evidence to deposit) and ukrns/design-as-function-of-evidence (which obligates action on deposits)
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    No service event is committed to without explicit two-axis costing (openness gain, governance cost) and a stated composition.  The composition is revisable in light of evidence; the current composition is published.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Closed-triangle complacency: local sustainability present but evidence never leaves the institution
    - Apex without governance: evidence deposited without the consent/data-sharing/attribution infrastructure to receive it
    - Deposit drift: events run without explicit costing; openness becomes a retrospective characterisation rather than a chosen position
    - Uniform-good fallacy: treating more openness as uniformly better; paying governance costs for low-information events and under-investing in the high-information ones that require real governance work
    - Post-dependent deposits: infrastructure that looked like ontogenetic accretion turns out to depend on a specific funded role (the ORCA lesson)
    - Uncosted governance: paying governance cost without a corresponding openness gain (ceremonial overhead)
  + ANCESTORS:
    - Krowne, A. P. (2003). An Architecture for Collaborative Math and Science Digital Libraries. Virginia Tech MS thesis.  (sustainability triangle)
    - UKRN WP §4 / draft-16-april §4 (triangle-to-tetrahedron; bootstrap sequence; openness/governance Pareto table; explicit Tension/Composition/Check)
    - UKRN role-codebook analysis (4/4 transcripts show EV_analyse absent; evidence apex absent across Cycle 0)
    - ORP evaluation ethics approval (King's College London, MRA-23/24-42968) — the existing governance surface on which low-cost deposits can run
    - equity/visible-impact (diagnoses the feedback failure this pattern answers)
    - equity/shared-maintenance (diagnoses the upstreaming failure this pattern partly answers)
    - Ostrom (1990) commons governance principles
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from UKRN WP §4 sustainability-tetrahedron analysis combined with the equity-domain visible-impact pattern's failure description.
    Mapped to the learning loop at the 'deposit' step: evidence produced must enter a shared layer to matter.
    Axis framing (openness ↔ governance cost) follows the paper-draft-16-april's Tension / Composition / Check structure; the real / irreducible / active defence of the axis is load-bearing and should not be collapsed into a single prescription.
    Coordination requirement: Low (Step 0 one-actor scaffold) to Very high (Step 3 multi-institution peer evaluation under network-level governance).
